\subsubsection{2018-07-05 Thursday}
\label{sec:orgd2afd7f}
\textit{<07/05/18 Thu>}

[Executive Summary]

What does is feel like to be wrong? According to Kathryn Schulz, "[being wrong] feels like being
right." In her 2011 TED talk entitled, "On Being Wrong," Schulz observes that the embarrassment or
dread that we typically associate with this state of mind does not arise in being wrong, but
instead in the realization we were wrong. 

I have been feeling as though the same can also be said about knowledge. What does it feel like to
be ignorant? Side-stepping trite answer to this that we all know, it can be just as unpleasant as
finding out you were wrong to realize that you don't really know a thing as well as you thought you
did. I imagine that the academic reader perhaps knows this feeling all too well, though I wish to
expand on being ignorant; it is just a special case of Schulz' "being wrong." The difference here is
that instead of finding yourself with similar confidence and a recently inverted opinion, you
discover a hole in your own credibility when it comes to forming an opinion. One could argue that
this kind of epistemological realization can be much, much more unsettling than the first.

I'm hoping to express that ignorance in the university classroom is not after all something to be
feared, but to be sought; once it is internally recognized, one is free to try and fill the gap with
new discoveries and understandings.

Understanding the pain of realization that comes to many who do not make it a habit to seek out
their flaws, an important tool in overcoming such feelings of solipsistic despair is deep, personal
and empathetic conversation with peers or even strangers. "Sonder" provides perhaps the single most
profound reason to include one's own capacity for skepticism in that of which she is skeptical.

Insofar as one manages to doubt all things, it may then become a timely endeavor to never utter a
lie; to do so would be to hold hostage any errors in the honest thoughts which go unsaid. To speak
or compose for review in an inauthentic manner would similarly be a surefire way to halt
intellectual growth in service of one's pride. As a fourth-year student - and I write knowing my own
pride to be a consideration - I have seen myself grow recently in transformative ways, proportional
to the percentage of my thoughts and actions that I will allow myself to doubt (while still unable
to properly express the reasons for my distaste for congratulations). 

A writing argument course should enable students to:
\begin{itemize}
\item learn how to recognize symptoms of ignorance within themselves
\item discover reasons to engage in compassionate discourse with fellow classmates and professors
\item always strive toward deeper understanding until needed to express an opinion
\item compare past and present work and find motivation in their capacities for intellectual growth
\end{itemize}

Or, in brief, to discover the \textbf{self}, \textbf{discourse}, \textbf{humility}, and \textbf{growth}.

The following criteria are proposed for each of the above learning goals. Throughout the course,
students should be encouraged to:
\begin{itemize}
\item seek out and embrace instances of failure in their own work
\item participate in peer-reviews of self-reflection writing
\item avoid pathological science and insincerity in the development of all written works
\item closely monitor and report any changes in rhetorical thought or writing abilities
\end{itemize}

